China is facing a water crisis due to rapid economic growth and a rising population.
To combat this, the government plans to reduce water consumption by 20% by 2010.
Despite increased grain production, China still faces a potential 48 million tonne shortage.
Climate change exacerbates the situation, with rising temperatures threatening food security.
The Yangtze River is experiencing record low water levels, impacting agriculture and wildlife.
Severe droughts have led to water shortages, affecting millions of people.
Desalination plants are being built to alleviate coastal water scarcity.
The Three Gorges Dam is not directly responsible for the water crisis.
